Conversation 1 (Emotional)
I failed my coding interview.

I'm sorry to hear that. Failing a coding interview is disappointing, especially if you put a lot of time into preparing.

One interview result doesn't tell you whether you can become a software engineer. It usually reflects a combination of preparation, interview fit, problem selection, and sometimes nerves.

A good way to turn this into progress is to figure out where things broke down. Common reasons include:

Problem-solving: You couldn't come up with an algorithm.
Data structures & algorithms: You knew the concept but couldn't apply it.
Coding: Too many syntax or implementation mistakes.
Communication: You solved the problem silently instead of explaining your thinking.
Time management: You spent too long on one approach.
Behavioral questions: You struggled to explain your experience.

If you can identify which of these happened, you can target your practice instead of starting from scratch.

Here are a few practical steps:

Write down every question you remember while it's fresh.
Solve those problems again without time pressure.
Review the concepts behind them.
Practice another mock interview, focusing on explaining your reasoning aloud.
Apply what you learned to your next interview.

Many experienced engineers have failed multiple interviews before landing great jobs. Interviewing is a skill that improves with deliberate practice.

If you're comfortable sharing, tell me:

What role was it for (internship, new grad, experienced)?
What coding question did they ask?
At what point did you get stuck?

We can go through it together step by step and turn it into a learning opportunity.

Conversation 2 (Technical)
What is React useEffect?

useEffect is a React Hook that lets you perform side effects in a function component.

A side effect is anything your component does besides calculating and displaying the UI, such as:

Fetching data from an API
Setting up timers (setInterval)
Adding event listeners
Updating the document title
Connecting to a WebSocket
Basic Syntax
import { useEffect } from "react";

function App() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Component rendered");
  });

  return <h1>Hello React</h1>;
}

Since no dependency array is provided, this effect runs after every render.

Example 1: Run only once

To run an effect only when the component first mounts, pass an empty dependency array.

import { useEffect } from "react";

function App() {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Runs only once");
  }, []);

  return <h1>Hello</h1>;
}

This is commonly used for:

Fetching initial data
Initializing a library
Example 2: Run when a value changes
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Count changed:", count);
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
      {count}
    </button>
  );
}

Here, the effect runs:

After the first render
Every time count changes
Example 3: Fetch data
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

function Users() {
  const [users, setUsers] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    async function fetchUsers() {
      const response = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users");
      const data = await response.json();
      setUsers(data);
    }

    fetchUsers();
  }, []);

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map(user => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}

The API is called only once when the component mounts.

Cleanup Function

Some effects need cleanup, such as removing event listeners or clearing timers.

useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    console.log("Tick");
  }, 1000);

  return () => {
    clearInterval(timer);
  };
}, []);

The cleanup function runs:

Before the effect runs again (if dependencies changed)
When the component unmounts
Dependency Array Summary
Dependency Array	When it runs
useEffect(fn)	After every render
useEffect(fn, [])	Once after the first render
useEffect(fn, [value])	After the first render and whenever value changes
Beginner Tips
Use useEffect for work that happens after rendering, like API calls or subscriptions.
Don't use useEffect for calculations that can be done directly during rendering.
Always include every value your effect uses in the dependency array unless you have a specific reason not to.

Think of it this way: React first renders your UI, and then useEffect runs afterward to perform any additional work, such as fetching data or interacting with the browser. This separation helps keep rendering predictable and your components easier to understand.

